==English==

===Etymology===
From {{suffix|en|antinomian|ism}}, coined by {{w|Martin Luther}}, notably used in his ''Against the Antinomians'' (1539).

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|en|/æntiˈnoʊmi.ənɪzəm/}}
* {{audio|en|En-us-antinomianism.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{hyphenation|en|an|ti|no|mi|an|ism}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{lb|en|Christianity}} The belief or teaching that because only the [[spiritual]] "law of faith" (Romans 3:27) is essential for [[salvation]], obedience to any practical or moral law has no role to play, even as a guide to conduct or as a test of the genuineness of [[faith]].
#: {{ant|en|legalism}}
